<h3 class="govuk-heading-m">Launch the preview</h3>

<ol class="govuk-list govuk-list--number govuk-list--spaced">
  <li>
    <strong>Open the preview</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      From the flow editor, click the <strong>Preview</strong> button (usually in the top toolbar). This opens a new tab showing the flow as an applicant would see it.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Start the application journey</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      The preview shows the flow in the citizen-facing format. You'll see:
    </p>
    <ul class="govuk-list govuk-list--bullet">
      <li><strong>Council branding</strong> — the NDX Demo Council name and logo</li>
      <li><strong>Clear question format</strong> — one question at a time, following GOV.UK design patterns</li>
      <li><strong>Help text</strong> — guidance for each question to help applicants answer correctly</li>
      <li><strong>Progress indication</strong> — showing where you are in the application</li>
    </ul>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Answer the questions</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Work through a few questions to see how the flow guides applicants. Try different answers to see how the routing works — for example, selecting different property types may lead to different follow-up questions.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Notice the data collection</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      As you answer questions, PlanX collects structured planning data. Each answer maps to a planning data field (like <code>property.type</code> or <code>proposal.description</code>). This structured data is what makes digital planning submissions machine-readable.
    </p>
  </li>

  <li>
    <strong>Compare editor and preview</strong>
    <p class="govuk-body">
      Switch between the editor tab and the preview tab. Notice how the nodes in the editor correspond to the questions in the preview. Any changes you made in Step 3 will be reflected in the preview.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>

